ign:left\" |{{Flag2|Morelos}}\n||12||1,903,811||0.6\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Oaxaca}}\n||22||3,967,889||0.6\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Tlaxcala}}\n||8||1,272,847||0.6\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Durango}}\n||8||1,754,754||0.5\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Michoac\u00e1n}}\n||24||4,584,471||0.5\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Tamaulipas}}\n||16||3,441,698||0.5\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Veracruz}}\n||35||8,112,505||0.4\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Zacatecas}}\n||7||1,579,209||0.4\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Chiapas}}\n||18||5,217,908||0.3\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Chihuahua}}\n||12||3,556,574||0.3\n|- style=\"text-align:left; padding-left:8px;\" class=\"sortbottom\"\n| style=\"width:360px;\" colspan=\"6\"| '''Source:''' \n<small>Secretariat of Health (2020).<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/><br>\nGeological and Atmospheric Research Institute <ref name=\"iigea1\"/><br>National Institute of Statistics and Geography <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cuentame.inegi.org.mx/poblacion/habitantes.aspx?tema=P |title=N\u00famero de habitantes. Cu\u00e9ntame de M\u00e9xico |publisher=Cuentame.inegi.org.mx |date=2005-04-02 |accessdate=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n|}\n\n=== Curve of infection ===\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type=line\n|linewidth=1\n|showSymbols=1\n|width=600\n|height=400\n|colors=#FF4343\n|showValues=\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|yAxisTitle=No. of cases\n|legend=Legend\n<!-- PLease clipboard copy the \"}x=...\" and \"y1=...\" lines from the log plot of total cases when you update these charts -->\n\n<!-- Search string CASES_X -->\n|x= Feb 28, Feb 29, Mar 1, Mar 6, Mar 7, Mar 11, Mar 12, Mar 13, Mar 14, Mar 15, Mar 16, Mar 17, Mar 18, Mar 19, Mar 20, Mar 21, Mar 22, Mar 23, Mar 24, Mar 25, Mar 26, Mar 27, Mar 28, Mar 29, Mar 30, Mar 32, Apr 1, Apr 2, Apr 3, Apr 4\n\n<!-- Search string CASES_Y -->\n|y1= 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 11, 15, 26, 41, 53, 82, 93, 118, 164, 203, 251, 316, 367, 405, 475, 585, 717, 848, 993, 1094, 1215, 1378, 1510, 1688, 1890\n\n|yScaleType=<!--log This is the line that makes this plot have a log axis, so leave it blank here!-->\n|y1Title=Total confirmed cases\n|yGrid= |xGrid=\n}}\n\n== Phases ==\nAccording to the Secretariat of Health, there are three phases before the disease (COVID-19) can be considered as an epidemic in the country:<ref name=\"phases\">{{cite web|url= https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/english/mexicos-covid-19-contingency-plan-three-key-phases-fight-coronavirus-outbreak|title= Mexico's covid-19 contingency plan: three key phases to fight the coronavirus outbreak|author=Teresa Moreno|date=March 14, 2020|website=El Universal}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"display: inline-table; font-size:90%; text-align:right;\"\n|-\n! colspan =\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:left;\" | Phase\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | Time period\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:left;\" | Description \n! rowspan=\"2\" | Ref\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center;\" | Start \n! style=\"text-align:center;\" | End\n|-\n! 1\u00b0\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | Viral Import\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | February 28, 2020\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | March 23, 2020<ref name=\"phase2\">{{cite web|url= https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/english/covid-19-mexico-has-entered-second-phase-its-contingency-plan |title= Covid-19: mexico has entered the second phase of its contingency plan |author=Newsroom & Agencies|date=March 24, 2020|website=El Universal}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | \n*People with the virus caught the disease outside Mexico and there are no cases of local transmission.\n*There is a limited number of people infected with the virus.\n*There are no strict restrictions for greeting people. \n*Public events in closed or open spaces are still allowed.\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:left\" | <ref name=\"phases\" />\n|-\n! 2\u00b0\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | Community Transmission\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | March 24, 2020<ref name=\"phase2\" />\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | [[TBA]]\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |\n* Community transmission cases are reported between people who have not had contact with foreigners.\n*The number of confirmed cases increases rapidly.\n*Massive public events are canceled both in open and closed spaces.\n*School classes are suspended and people are encouraged to work from home. \n|-\n! 3\u00b0\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | Epidemic\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | [[TBA]]\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | [[TBA]]\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |\n* Thousands of cases are reported in multiple locations across the country.\n*Schools and workplaces with active outbreaks would have no activities.\n* It requires the implementation of stricter health protocols.\n* In the worst case scenario it would be required a general quarantine of the population.\n|}\n\n==Economic effects==\n{{See also|Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Financial impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nThe [[National Institute of Statistics and Geography (Mexico)|INEGI]] says the unemployment rate increased from 3.6% in January 2020 to 3.7% in February 2020. The informal sector increased to 56.3% in February compared to 56.0% in February 2019.<ref>[https://www.tvazteca.com/aztecanoticias/finanzas/notas/aumenta-el-desempleo-en-mexico?fbclid=IwAR2eO0b2MXeWkJ0JegBEJNrXILvvAH1frrw1IFAF47gKBLfQoAVBA5LaJas Unemployment increases in Mexico] {{in lang|es}} Azteca Noticias, 26 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nThe [[Mexican Stock Exchange]] fell to a record low on 10 March due to fears of the coronavirus and because of [[2020 Russia\u2013Saudi Arabia oil price war|falling oil prices]]. The [[Bank of Mexico|Bank of Mexico (Banxico)]] stepped in to prop up the value of the peso, which fell 14% to 22.929 per US dollar.<ref name=\"banixco\"/> World markets are seeing falls similar to those of 1987.<ref>[https://www.dineroenimagen.com/blogs/colegio-de-contadores-publicos-de-mexico-ac/historico-el-covid-19-provoca-la-mayor-crisis-en Historical! COVID-19 causes the biggest crisis in global financial markets] {{in lang|es}} by COLEGIO DE CONTADORES P\u00daBLICOS DE M\u00c9XICO, A.C., Dinero en Imagen, 18 Mar 2020</ref> [[Moody's Investors Service]] predicted that the economy will contract 5.2% during the first trimester of the year and 3.7% by the end of the year.<ref>[https://www.infobae.com/america/mexico/2020/03/25/economia-de-mexico-caera-37-por-coronavirus-moodys/ Mexico's economy will drop 3.7% due to coronavirus: Moody\u2019s] {{in lang|es}} Infobae, 25 Mar 2020</ref> Banxico announced on 1 April that foreign investors have withdrawn MXN $150 billion (US $,6.3 billion) from Mexico, mostly in ''Certificados de la Tesorer\u00eda'' ((Treasury Certificates, Cetes) since February 27 when the first COVID-19 case in Mexico was diagnosed. The problem is compounded by the low oil price, only US $10.37 per barrel, a 20.29% drop since the beginning of the [[2020 Russia\u2013Saudi Arabia oil price war]].<ref>[https://www.infobae.com/america/mexico/2020/04/01/coronavirus-en-mexico-extranjeros-retiran-150-mmdp-del-pais-por-covid-19/ Coronavirus in Mexico: foreigners withdraw 150 mmdp from the country for COVID-19] {{in lang|es}} Infoabe Mexico, 1 April 2020</ref> \n\nOn 24 March, [[Grupo Modelo]], makers of [[Corona (beer)|Corona beer]], promised to donate 300,000 bottles of antibacterial gel to the [[Mexican Social Security Institute|Mexican Social Security Institute (IMSS)]].<ref>[https://www.sinembargo.mx/24-03-2020/3754411?fbclid=IwAR2qx4vzr-sOgF5mF2IjD2EFAz5_Tq-OZAFpF6irpufZBsavsysjswaMYLk Grupo Modelo donar\u00e1 300 mil botellas de gel antibacterial al IMSS para combatir al COVID-19]{{in lang|es}} Sin Embargo, 24 Mar 2020</ref> The ''Conacintra'' (National Chamber of the Processing Industry) announced on 2 April they were suspending all beer production in the country, as breweries are not an essential industry and there was sufficient supply in the country for a month.<ref>[https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/cartera/coronavirus-no-se-producira-cerveza-durante-un-mes-informa-canacintra Beer will not be produced for a month; Not an essential activity: Canacintra] {{in lang|es}} El Universal, 2 Apr 2020</ref> Tequila producers plan to stay open.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-mexico-tequila/mexican-tequila-makers-unlike-brewers-plan-to-keep-up-production-exports-idUSKBN21M0SU Mexican tequila makers, unlike brewers, plan to keep up production, exports] Reuters, 4 Apr 2020</ref>\n\nThe ''Consejo Nacional Empresarial Tur\u00edstico'' (National Tourism Business Council, CNET) sent two letters in March to [[Alfonso Romo]], Chief of Staff to the President, outlining the importance of tourism to the economy and asking for government support for the sector. Tourism provides 4 million jobs in Mexico, and 93% of the companies have ten or fewer employees. COVID-19 has forced the closure of 4,000 hotels (52,400 rooms) and 2,000 restaurants, while the airline industry has lost MXN $30 billion (US $1.3 billion).<ref>[https://www.dineroenimagen.com/carlos-velazquez/el-cnet-pide-apoyo-mientras-sus-empresas-salvan-empleos/120918 The CNET asks for support while their companies save jobs] {{in lang|en}} by Carlos Velazquez, Dinero en Imagen, 26 Mar 2020</ref> Tourism accounts for 10% of [[Gross domestic product|Gross domestic product (GDP)]] in the world.<ref>[https://www.dineroenimagen.com/maricarmen-cortes/turismo-en-riesgo-el-10-del-pib-mundial/120916 Tourism: 10% of world GDP at risk] {{in lang|en}} by Maricarmen Cortes, Dinero en Imagen, 26 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nThe association of car dealers, ADMA, predicts a decrease in sales in Mexico between 16% and 25% this year.<ref>[https://www.dineroenimagen.com/jose-yuste/desesperacion-de-industrias/120857?utm_source=dineroenimagen_desktop&utm_campaign=relacionados&utm_medium=article Despair of industries] {{in lang|en}} by Jos\u00e9 Yuste, Dinero en Imagen, 25 Mar 2020</ref> [[J.D. Power]] estimated a 20% decrease, 264,000 vehicles, in Mexico and a 15% drop across the world.<ref>[https://www.forbes.com.mx/economia-caida-venta-autos-mexico-20-coronavirus/ Car sales in Mexico will fall 20% due to coronavirus: JD Power] {{in lang|es}} Forbes Mexico, 1 April 2020</ref> The [[Coparmex|Employers Confederation of the Mexican Republic (COPARMEX)]] criticized the government on 29 March for not suspending the payment of taxes, saying the government does not care about unemployment. Fernando Trevi\u00f1o N\u00fa\u00f1ez, president of the organization, explained that businesses cannot afford to pay salaries for more than three months without receiving income.<ref>[https://www.milenio.com/negocios/sin-rumbo-el-gobierno-federal-ante-la-pandemia-coparmex Sin rumbo, el gobierno federal ante la pandemia: Coparmex] {{in lang|es}} by  Ang\u00e9lica Tenahua, Milenio, 29 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nPanic buying in mid-March is causing shortages in Mexico of [[Hydroxychloroquine]] and [[azithromycin]], which U.S. President Donald Trump, with no backing from the scientific or medical communities, says is helpful in preventing COVID-19. The ''Comisi\u00f3n Federal para la Protecci\u00f3n de Riesgos Sanitarios'' (Federal Commission for the Protection of Health Risks, Cofepris) has put controls on the sale of both products. Hidroxicloroquina is used in the treatment of [[malaria]], [[lupus]] and [[rheumatoid arthritis]]. Plaquenil tablets are produced in Mexico by the French company [[Sanofi]]; the raw material comes from [[Hungary]]. Shortages of medicine for these diseases can be expected soon.<ref name=panic>[https://www.dineroenimagen.com/jose-yuste/compras-de-panico-escasean-la-hidroxicloroquina/120913 Compras de p\u00e1nico escasean la hidroxicloroquina] {{in lang|en}} by Jos\u00e9 Yuste, Dinero en Imagen, 26 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nGasoline and diesel fuel importers have not noted a decrease in demand since the onset of the COVID-19 pandemic, and they fear that health precautions could cause fuel delays at ports of entry. [[Watco Companies]] said that cargo on the [[Houston Ship Channel]] for delivery to San Luis Potos\u00ed increased 25% in March compared to January. Mexico imports 65% of its gasoline.<ref>[https://www.infobae.com/america/mexico/2020/03/26/crecen-temores-entre-importadores-de-gasolina-por-caida-en-la-demanda/ Fears Grow Among Gasoline Importers Due to Demand Drop] {{in lang|en}} By Amy Stillman & Jeffrey Bair, Bloomberg/Inforbae, 26 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nSome financial analysts say there has been too little, too late. Carlos Serrano of [[BBVA M\u00e9xico]] predicts a 4.5% economic contraction in 2020, while analysts at [[Capital Economics]] in London argue that the government has to do more to support the economy. They forecast a 6% contraction this year. HR Ratings, Latin America\u2019s first credit rating agency, said that the performance of the economy this year will depend on the government\u2019s response to the COVID-19 crisis.<ref>{{cite web |website=Mexico News Daily|title=While WHO praises virus response, financial analysts say it's too slow|date=March 26, 2020|language=en |url=https://mexiconewsdaily.com/news/coronavirus/who-praises-virus-response/}}</ref>\n\t\nAuthorities are concerned about supermarket robberies. A gang of 70 people robbed a grocery store in [[Tec\u00e1mac]], State of Mexico, on March 23, and a gang of 30 looted a supermarket in [[Oaxaca City]] on March 24. Calls for supermarket looting, warning of food shortages, are making the rounds of social media.<ref>[https://mexiconewsdaily.com/news/30-break-into-and-loot-oaxaca-supermarket-2/ 30 people break into and loot Oaxaca supermarket] Mexico News Daily, 25 Mar 2020  [https://apnews.com/5625bb27578887acbb834bd99bfccaaa Mexico police investigate store robberies as virus spreads] AP, 25 March 2020</ref> Four such social media groups in Tijuana were broken up in Baja California on 29 March.<ref>[https://www.msn.com/es-mx/noticias/mexico/frustran-saqueos-a-tiendas-en-tijuana/ar-BB11SNZj Frustran saqueos a tiendas en Tijuana] {{in lang|es}} Excelsior, 29 Mar 2020</ref>\n\n==Government response==\n*9 January, 2020 \u2013 A travel advisory for people traveling to or from China was issued.<ref name=indigo />\n*22 January \u2013 The [[Secretariat of Health (Mexico)|Secretariat of Health]] issued a statement saying that the novel coronavirus COVID-19 did not present a danger to Mexico.<ref name=indigo>{{cite web |url=https://www.reporteindigo.com/piensa/el-nuevo-virus-coronavirus-no-representa-un-peligro-para-mexico/ |title=El Nuevo Virus Coronavirus No Representa Un Peligro Para M\u00e9xico |trans-title=The New Coronavirus Does Not Represent a Danger for Mexico |language=Spanish |work=Reporte de Indigo |date=22 January 2020 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n*30 January \u2013 The Government of Mexico designed a ''Preparation and Response Plan'' that was made by the National Committee for Health Safety, a working group led by Secretariat of Health composed by different health entities aiming to act upon the imminent arrival of the pandemic. This group carried out a series of alert measures, rehabilitation and updating of epidemiological regulations based on the International Health Regulations.<ref name=salud>{{cite web|url=http://www.gob.mx/salud/prensa/033-mexico-esta-preparado-para-enfrentar-coronavirus-2019-ncov|title=M\u00e9xico est\u00e1 preparado para enfrentar coronavirus (2019-nCoV) (Mexico is prepared to face coronavirus)|publisher=Secretariat of Health|date=|website=gob.mx|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n*5 March \u2013 The National Governors' Conference (Conago) met to discuss the coronavirus outbreak. The directors of INSABI, IMSS and ISSSTE also participated.<ref name=conago/>\n*6 March \u2013 [[Hugo L\u00f3pez-Gatell Ram\u00edrez]] led the first daily press conference on COVID-19.<ref name=nat_coun_health />\n*10 March \u2013 As the stock market and the price of oil fell, \u2018\u2018Banxico\u2019\u2019 stepped in to prop up the value of the peso, which had fallen 14%.<ref name=banixco />\n*13 March \u2013 The National Autonomous University of Mexico suspended in-person classes. Authorities canceled or postponed major tourist events in Guadalajara and Merida.<ref name=cancelations />\n*14 March\n**The SEP announced that all sporting and civic events in schools would be canceled<ref name=sep /> and that Easter break, originally planned from 6 to 17 April, would be extended from 20 March to 20 April.<ref name=\"Prevention Easter break in schools\" /> On 31 March the school closings were extended through 30 April.<ref>[https://www.informador.mx/mexico/Casos-positivos-de-COVID-19-en-Mexico-ascienden-a-mil-215-20200331-0171.html Positive cases of COVID-19 in Mexico amount to 1,215] {{in lang|es}} Informador, 31 Mar 2020</ref>\n**The SCHP announced it was taking measures to prevent a 0.5% fall in GDP.<ref name=schp /> \n**The \u2018\u2018Universidad Aut\u00f3noma de Nuevo Le\u00f3n\u2019\u2019 (UANL) suspended classes for its more than 206,000 students starting on March 17.<ref name=uanl />\n*15 March \u2013 [[List of heads of government of Mexico City|Mexico City mayor]] Claudia Sheinbaum declared that Mexico City expected to spend an extra MXN $100 million to prevent the spread of COVID-19.<ref name=sheinbaum />\n*18 March \u2013 Authorities announced that they were looking for hundreds of citizens who might be carriers of the coronavirus, especially in the states of Puebla, Jalisco, Aguascalientes and Guerrero. The Autonomous University of Guerrero (UAGRO) in Chilpancingo closed after a female student tested positive for the virus.<ref name=look />\n*22 March\n**Bars, nightclubs, movie theaters and museums were closed in Mexico City.<ref name=bars /> \n**Governor Alfaro Ram\u00edrez announces that [[Jalisco]] and seven other states would block flights from areas such as that had a high rate of coronavirus. He also said that they would purchase 25,000 testing kits.<ref name=planes />\n**Governor [[Jaime Rodr\u00edguez Calder\u00f3n]] of Nuevo Le\u00f3n said he will not rule out the use of force to get people to stay at home.<ref>[https://www.excelsior.com.mx/nacional/el-bronco-no-descarta-usar-fuerza-publica-para-que-se-cumpla-aislamiento/1371423 \u2018El Bronco\u2019 no descarta usar fuerza p\u00fablica para que se cumpla aislamiento] {{in lang|es}} by ARACELY GARZA, Reuters/Excelsior, 22 Mar 2020, retrieved 28 Mar 2020</ref>\n*23 March\n**The WHO announced that Mexico had entered into the community contact phase of infection.<ref name=who />\n**The National Campaign of Healthy Distancing, a national program of non-pharmaceutical measures based on [[social distancing]], began.<ref name=social/> A media campaign led by \"Susana Distancia\", who is a fictional female superhero aiming to promote social distancing, was launched.<ref name=susana /> \"Susana Distancia\" is in fact a [[Word play|wordplay]] roughly meaning \"(maintaining) a healthy distance\".\n**Access to supermarkets, drugstores and convenience stores in Coahuila was limited to one person per family, and the temperature of that person was taken before entering.<ref name=supermarket />\n*24 March \u2013 President [[Andr\u00e9s Manuel L\u00f3pez Obrador|L\u00f3pez Obrador]] announced that Mexico had entered Phase 2 of the coronavirus pandemic, in effect until April 30. Gatherings of more than 100 people were prohibited, and both the [[Mexican Army]] and the [[Mexican Navy]] would participate.<ref name=amlo_phase2 />\n*25 March\n**President L\u00f3pez Obrador ordered the Mexican Air Force to rescue Mexicans trapped in Argentina.<ref name=airforce /> \n**[[PROFECO|Office of the Federal Prosecutor for the Consumer (Profeco)]] closed two businesses in [[Tijuana]], Baja California, for price-gouging.<ref name=profecobc /> \n**In Mexico City, Claudia Sheinbaum announced financial support for families and micro industries affected by the pandemic, and she suspended automobile smog checks through April 19. She closed movie theaters, bars, nightclubs, gyms and other entertainment centers.<ref name=finsupport />\n**The government announced that it would continue receiving [[2020 coronavirus pandemic on cruise ships|cruise ships]] \u201cfor humanitarian reasons,\u201d but that passengers would be individually \"fumigated\" before being taken directly to airports to be returned to their home countries. The protocol will apply to the {{ship|MS|Europa}}, currently docked in Puerta Vallarta.<ref name=sea>[https://apnews.com/01aea6b6217f0464be47180c27af389f Mexico will receive cruise ships, but fumigate passengers] AP, 25 Mar 2020</ref>\n*26 March\n**President L\u00f3pez Obrador addressed the [[G20|Group of Twenty]] regarding medical supplies and trade and tariffs.<ref name=g20 /> The federal government announced it would suspend most sectors' activities from 26 March to 19 April.<ref name=suspend_govt /> \n**The Secretary of Health estimated that Phase 3 of the pandemic, when the number of cases reaches its peak, will be about 19 April.<ref name=peak /> \n**Authorities in Chihuahua announced that it would start to quarantine migrants who were returned to the Ciudad Ju\u00e1rez border crossing.<ref name=chi />\n**The ''Comisi\u00f3n Federal para la Protecci\u00f3n de Riesgos Sanitarios'' (Federal Commission for the Protection of Health Risks, Cofepris) put controls on the sale of hidroxicloroquina and azithromycin, used in the treatment of malaria, lupus]] and rheumatoid arthritis, but not shown to be effective against [[COVID-19]]. Nonetheless, panic buying of these medicines is likely to soon lead to a shortage.<ref name=panic />\n*27 March\n** President L\u00f3pez Obrador practiced social distancing during his tour in [[Nayarit]]. The president had been widely criticized for shaking hands, kissing and hugging as he met with people.<ref name=distance>[https://politica.expansion.mx/presidencia/2020/03/27/en-gira-por-nayarit-amlo-aplica-sana-distancia-recomendada-por-coronavirus En gira por Nayarit, AMLO aplica \"sana distancia\" recomendada por coronavirus] {{in lang|es}} Expansi\u00f3n Politica, 27 Mar 2020</ref>\n**The federal government bought 5,000 [[ventilator]]s from China.<ref name=ventilator>[https://politica.expansion.mx/presidencia/2020/03/27/gobierno-compra-5-000-ventiladores-a-china-para-enfrentar-coronavirus Gobierno compra 5,000 ventiladores a China para enfrentar coronavirus] {{in lang|es}} Expansi\u00f3n Politica, 27 Mar 2020</ref>\n**Profeco (Office of the Federal Prosecutor for the Consumer) announced it would fine merchants who unfairly raised the prices on household goods.<ref name=fine />\n**[[V\u00edctor Villalobos Ar\u00e1mbula]], [[Secretariat of Agriculture and Rural Development (Mexico)|Secretary of Agriculture and Rural Development (SADER)]] met with food producers to discuss guaranteeing the food supply in spite of the pandemic.<ref>[https://www.jornada.com.mx/ultimas/economia/2020/03/27/sader-delimita-acciones-para-garantizar-abasto-de-alimentos-6457.html Sader delimita acciones para garantizar abasto de alimentos] {{in lang|es}} by  Carolina G\u00f3mez Mena, La Jornada, 27 Mar 2020</ref>\n*March 28\n**[[Hugo L\u00f3pez-Gatell Ram\u00edrez]], Deputy Secretary of Health, said that with 16 deaths and 848 cases of infection, this is the last opportunity to prevent accelerated growth of COVID-19. He called on the population to act responsibly to prevent its spread.<ref>[https://aristeguinoticias.com/2803/mexico/ultima-oportunidad-de-evitar-crecimiento-acelerado-de-covid-19-lopez-gatell-van-16-muertes-y-848-contagiados/ \u00daltima oportunidad de evitar crecimiento acelerado de COVID-19: L\u00f3pez-Gatell; van 16 muertes y 848 contagiados] {{in lang|es}} Arestegui Noticias, 28 Mar 2020</ref> ''[[Milenio]]'' reported that L\u00f3pez-Gatell said there is a legal basis for the use of force to enforce stay-at-home orders during the COVID-19 pandemic.<ref>[https://www.milenio.com/politica/covid-19-fuerza-publica-mantener-gente-casa?fbclid=IwAR04pAvd6BR_KgpwKq1ENodfpqbP7D_-isW2C01gBO09mXE9641H_gc1Pig \u00daltima oportunidad para permanecer en casa: L\u00f3pez Gatell] {{in lang|es}} by Fanny Miranda, Milenio, 28 Mar 2020</ref>\n**Health officials, accompanied by a representative of the military and Foreign Secretary [[Marcelo Ebrard]] made a video urging the populace to stay home. AMLO did not appear in that video, but he made a separate one with the same message.<ref>[https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/border-baja-california/story/2020-03-28/in-tijuana-video-address-mexicos-president-toughens-coronavirus-stance In Tijuana video address, Mexico\u2019s president toughens coronavirus stance] {{in lang|en}} By WENDY FRY, The San Diego Union-Tribune, 28 Mar 2020</ref>\n*30 March \u2013 A national health emergency was declared in Mexico and stricter measures aimed at containing the spread of the virus were introduced.<ref name=\"30march\" />\n*1 April\n**Beaches throughout the country are closed.<ref>[https://www.informador.mx/mexico/Anuncia-Salud-cierre-de-playas-ante-emergencia-por-COVID-19-20200401-0016.html Anuncia Salud cierre de playas ante emergencia por COVID-19] {{in lang|es}} Notimex/Informador, 1 April 2020</ref>\n**INEGI asked everyone who has not taken part of the 2020 census to contact them via their webpage or by calling them before 15 April.<ref>[https://www.milenio.com/politica/comunidad/coronavirus-inegi-pide-entregar-informacion-internet Inegi pide a ciudadanos censarse por internet antes del 15 de abril] {{in lang|es}} Milenio, 1 April 2020</ref>\n**The [[Governor of Nuevo Le\u00f3n]] ordered a halt to production and distribution of beer in the state, beginning April 3.<ref>[https://www.forbes.com.mx/economia-gobierno-nuevo-leon-anuncia-paro-produccion-distribucion-cerveza-pais/?fbclid=IwAR2zgxuKOiLAUhzQ44bbhpf-I1_S461Doh-QPdobMaMDLvm8ZclmNr9egvU NL government anticipates high production and distribution of alcoholic beverages throughout the country] {{in lang|es}} Forbes Mexico, 1 April 2020</ref>\n*3 April \u2013 AMLO issues a decree to abolish 100 public trusts related to science and culture; the [[Secretariat of Finance and Public Credit|Fianance Ministry (SHCP) will receive the money directly.<ref>[https://www.la-prensa.com.mx/mexico/politica/amlo-emite-decreto-para-extincion-de-fideicomisos-publicos-5053897.html AMLO issues decree for the extinction of public trusts] {{in lang|es}} by Carlos Lara, El Sol de M\u00e9xico, 3 Apr 2020</ref> The move is expected to MXN save $250 billion (US $10 billion) which can be spent to strengthen the economy, pay for social programs and pay off the debt.<ref>[https://www.elsoldemexico.com.mx/finanzas/con-extincion-de-fideicomisos-se-ahorraran-250-mil-mdp-amlo-5054241.html With extinction of trusts 250 thousand mp will be saved: AMLO] {{in lang|es}} by Sarahi Uribe, El Sol de M\u00e9xico, 3 Apr 2020</ref>\n*Claudia Sheinbaum promised to donate two months of her salary (a total of MXN $156,728) to the struggle against COVID-19 and invited other officials to do so also.<ref>[https://www.elsoldemexico.com.mx/metropoli/cdmx/sheinbaum-donara-dos-meses-de-su-salario-para-enfrentar-covid-19-5058851.html Sheinbaum donar\u00e1 dos meses de su salario para enfrentar Covid-19] {{in lang|es}} by Israel Zamarr\u00f3n, El Sol de M\u00e9xico, 4 Apr 2020</ref>\n\n==Cancellations, suspensions, and closings==\n{{Main|List of events affected by the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{See also|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on education|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema}}\n\n;Archaeological sites\nTeotihuac\u00e1n, Xochicalco, El Tepozteco closed 21\u201322 March. Chich\u00e9n Itz\u00e1 closed indefinitely starting 21 March.<ref name=inah />\n;Educational institutions\n:'''Basic education'''The SEP announced on 14 March that all sporting and civic events in schools would be cancelled<ref name=sep /> and that Easter break would be from 20 March to 20 April.<ref name=\"Prevention Easter break in schools\" /> \n:'''Higher education''': The [[National Autonomous University of Mexico|UNAM]] and [[Monterrey Institute of Technology and Higher Education|Tec de Monterrey]], switched to virtual classes on 13 March.<ref name=cancelations /> Autonomous University of the State of Morelos, (UAEM) suspended classes on 16 March.<ref name=uaem /> Autonomous University of Nuevo Leon, (UANL) suspended classes from 17 March to 20 April.<ref name=uanl /> Autonomous University of Guerrero (UAGRO) and Technical Institute of Guerrero ([[Chilpancingo]]) closed 18 March.<ref name=look />\n;Entertainment\n[[Grupo CIE|OCESA]] cancelled all its events until April 19.<ref name=ocesa>{{cite web|website=El Universal|language=es|trans-title=Ocesa suspends all its events until April 19 due to the coronavirus|title=Ocesa suspende todos sus eventos hasta el 19 de abril por el coronavirus |date=March 16, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020|url=https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/espectaculos/musica/ocesa-suspende-sus-eventos-hasta-el-19-de-abril-por-el-coronavirus}}</ref>\n:'''Fairs''': Authorities announced on 14 March they were considering the cancellation of the ''Festival Internacional de Cine de Guadalajara''. In M\u00e9rida, the ''Tianguis Tur\u00edstico'' was postponed to September.<ref name=cancelations /> \n:'''Musical''': ''[[Chicago (musical)|Chicago]]'' suspended until 17 April<ref name=ocesa />\n:'''Concerts''': [[The Magic Numbers]], [[Los Tigres del Norte]], Red Orange County {{sic}}, [[Mercury Rev]], Mar\u00eda Le\u00f3n, [[Sasha Sloan]]<ref name=ocesa /> and [[Ricky Martin]]<ref>[https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/espectaculos/musica/coronavirus-ricky-martin-cancela-conciertos-en-mexico Ricky Martin cancels all his concerts in Mexico due to coronavirus] {{in lang|es}} El Universal, 13 Mar 2020</ref>\n:'''Conference''': [[Michelle Obama]]<ref name=ocesa />\n:'''Other''': Bars, nightclubs, movie theaters, and museums were closed in Mexico City on 22 March.<ref name=bars />\n;Government\nPresident L\u00f3pez Obrador suspended non-essential activities from 26 March to 19 April. The health and energy sectors, the oil industry, and public services such as water supply, waste management and public safety continued to function.<ref name=suspend_govt />\n;Industry\nFord Motor Company, Honda and Audi closed their manufacturing plants in Mexico on 18 March.<ref name=ford /> Hundreds of hotel employees in [[Canc\u00fan]] were fired.<ref name=cancun /> Alsea ([[Starbucks]], VIPS, [[Domino's Pizza]], [[Burger King]], Italianni's, [[Chili's]], [[California Pizza Kitchen]], [[P. F. Chang's China Bistro]] and [[The Cheesecake Factory]]) offered its employees unpaid leave.<ref name=alsea /> PROFECO closed two businesses in Tijuana Baja California, for price-gouging on 25 March.<ref name=profecobc /> [[Cin\u00e9polis]] announced that they will temporaily close all of their theaters starting March 25.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cin\u00e9polis regresar\u00e1 el dinero de boletos programados |url=https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/espectaculos/cine/cinepolis-regresara-el-dinero-de-boletos-programados|website=El Universal|date=March 24, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020|language=es}}</ref>\n;Ports of entry\n:'''Air''': Governor Alfaro Ram\u00edrez of Jalisco announced that beginning Thursday, 26 March, eight states in the [[Baj\u00edo]] and western Mexico woud block flights from areas that had a high rate of coronavirus. The restrictions would apply at the [[Miguel Hidalgo y Costilla Guadalajara International Airport]] and the [[Licenciado Gustavo D\u00edaz Ordaz International Airport]] in Puerto Vallarta.<ref name=planes />\n:'''Land''': The [[United States Department of State]] announced on 20 March there would be restrictions on travel across the Mexico\u2013United States border. The restrictions would not apply to cargo.<ref name=pompeo /> On 26 March, protesters in Sonora insisted that the government limit [[Mexico\u2013United States border|border crossings]] with the United States.<ref name=border /> Chihuahua (state) announced that it would start to quarantine migrants who are returned to the Ciudad Ju\u00e1rez border crossing.<ref name=chi /> Citizens of Nogales, Sonora, blocked border crossing from Nogales, Arizona, in order to prevent the entrance of individuals with the virus infection and to prevent shortages of food, bottled water, toilet paper and cleaning supplies in local stores.<ref name=nogales />\n:'''Sea''': The government announced on 25 March it would continue receiving cruise ships but that passengers would be individually \"fumigated\" before being taken directly to airports to be returned to their home countries.<ref name=sea />\n;Sports\n[[Jalisco Open]] (tennis tournament) and [[CONCACAF Champions League]] (soccer) cancelled 13 March<ref name=cancelations />\n;Religious events\nOn 17 March, [[Passion Play of Iztapalapa]] in Mexico City moved to an undisclosed location indoors and televised on April 10<ref>{{cite web|website=[[La Jornada]]|title=Suspenden Viacrucis de Iztapalapa; actos a puerta cerrada y v\u00eda tv |language=es|trans-title=Way of the Cross of Iztapalapa suspended; acts behind closed doors and via tv|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020 |url=https://www.jornada.com.mx/ultimas/capital/2020/03/17/cancelan-viacrucis-de-iztapalapa-5742.html}}</ref>\n\nSan Luis Potosi suspended wakes and funerals on March 29.<ref name=funeral />\n;Curfew established\nMayor Juanita Romero ([[National Action Party (Mexico)|PAN]]) of Nacozari de Garc\u00eda, Sonora, declared a curfew in effect until 20 April.<ref name=curfew />\n\n== Notable Mexicans with COVID-19 ==\n{{Div col}}\n*Alejandra Ag\u00fcayo, newscaster ([[FOROtv]])<ref name=famous>[https://www.infobae.com/america/entretenimiento/2020/03/27/famosos-mexicanos-con-coronavirus-y-como-enfrentan-su-aislamiento/ Famous Mexicans with coronaviruses and how they face their isolation] {{in lang|es}} Infobae, 27 Mar 2020</ref>\n*Jorge Alcib\u00edades Garcia, [[Chamber of Deputies (Mexico)|federal deputy]]<ref name=mil />\n*[[Esteban Arce]], newscaster (''Expreso de la ma\u00f1ana'')<ref name=famous />\n*Mariana Arceo, Mexican [[Pentathlon|pentathelete]] ([[Mexico at the 2020 Summer Olympics|2020 Olympic Team]])<ref name=mil>[https://www.milenio.com/espectaculos/coronavirus-politicos-famosos-y-deportistas-que-han-dado-positivo Athletes, politicians and celebrities who have tested positive for coronavirus] {{in lang|es}} Milenio, 26 Mar 2020</ref>\n*Juan Domingo Beckmann, businessperson ([[Jose Cuervo]] tequila)<ref name=placido />\n*[[Patricio Borghetti]], television presenter (''Venga la Alegr\u00eda''; TV Azteca)<ref>[https://www.infobae.com/america/entretenimiento/2020/03/26/nada-que-un-taco-no-solucione-otro-dia-en-la-cuarentena-por-coronavirus-de-odalys-ramirez-y-patricio-borghetti/ \"Nothing that a taco does not solve\": another day in the quarantine for coronavirus of Odalys Ram\u00edrez and Patricio Borghetti] {{in lang|es}} Infobae, 26 Mar 2020</ref>\n*[[Placido Domingo]], 79, Spanish tenor who lives in Mexico<ref name=placido>[https://www.lavanguardia.com/musica/20200328/48130404682/placido-domingo-coronavirus.html Pl\u00e1cido Domingo, admitted to Acapulco for complications associated with Covid-19] {{in lang|es}} La Vanguardia, 28 Mar 2020</ref>\n*[[Francisco Dom\u00ednguez Servi\u00e9n]], [[Governor of Quer\u00e9taro]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.radioformula.com.mx/noticias/20200330/francisco-dominguez-servien-coronavirus-covid-19-gobernador-queretaro-mexico/|date=30 March 2020|title=Gobernador de Quer\u00e9taro da positivo en coronavirus|agency=radioformula|author=Itzel Garc\u00eda}} {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n*[[Omar Fayad]], [[List of Governors of Hidalgo|Governor of Hidalgo]]<ref>[https://politica.expansion.mx/estados/2020/03/28/el-gobernador-de-hidalgo-omar-fayad-esta-enfermo-de-coronavirus-amlo-mananera-covid-19 The Governor of Hidalgo, Omar Fayad, is sick with coronavirus] {{in lang|es}} Expansi\u00f3n Politica, 28 Mar 2020</ref>\n*Horacio Franco, flautist and director (''Capella Varroca M\u00e9xico'')<ref name=famous />\n*Mar\u00eda Fritz Sierra, General Secretary of the government of [[Yucatan]]<ref>https://www.milenio.com/politica/coronavirus-mexico-31-marzo-casos-noticias-hora-vivo Secretary General of the Yucatan government tests positive for COVID-19] Milenio, 31 Mar 2020</ref>{{better source|date=April 2020}}\n*[[Danna Garc\u00eda]], Colombian actress who resides in Mexico (''El Se\u00f1or de los Cielos'')<ref>[https://www.infobae.com/america/entretenimiento/2020/03/16/danna-garcia-dio-positivo-a-coronavirus-se-mantiene-en-aislamiento-pero-optimista/ Danna Garc\u00eda tested positive for coronavirus: remains in isolation, but optimistic] {{in lang|es}} Infobae, 16 Mar 2020, retrieved 29 Mar 2020</ref>\n*Mar\u00eda Libier Gonz\u00e1lez Anaya, federal deputy<ref name=dep />\n*[[Jolette (singer)|Jolette]], singer, television presenter, and reality star (''[[La Academia]]'' 2005)<ref name=razon>[https://www.razon.com.mx/entretenimiento/ellos-son-los-famosos-en-mexico-que-se-han-infectado-de-covid-19/ These are the famous Mexicans who have been infected with COVID-19] {{in lang|es}} La Raz\u00f3n, 27 Mar 2020</ref>\n*Jos\u00e9 Kuri Harfush, businessperson ([[Inbursa]])<ref name=univision />\n*Hilde Lara, singer with Yndio<ref name=famous /> \n*[[Ad\u00e1n Augusto L\u00f3pez Hern\u00e1ndez]], [[Governor of Tabasco]]<ref name=loppez_hernandez />\n*Alberto Marrero, businessperson (CEO [[Atl\u00e9tico San Luis]])<ref name=mil />\n*Audomaro P\u00e9rez, 72, bass player ([[Yndio]])<ref name=famous />\n*Mar\u00eda de Jes\u00fas Rosete S\u00e1nchez, federal deputy<ref name=dep>[https://www.msn.com/es-mx/noticias/mexico/legisladora-del-pes-da-positivo-de-covid-19-ya-son-3-diputados/ar-BB11T7rR PES legislator tests positive for Covid-19; now there are 3 deputies] {{in lang|es}} La Jornada, 29 Mar 2020</ref>\n*Jaime Ruiz Sacrist\u00e1n, businessperson (CEO [[Mexican Stock Exchange]])<ref name=univision>[https://www.univision.com/radio/radio-nacional/el-covid-19-no-perdona-camila-sodi-y-otros-famosos-mexicanos-afectados-por-el-coronavirus-fotos \ud83d\udcf8 COVID-19 does not forgive: Camila Sodi and other famous Mexicans affected by the coronavirus] {{in lang|es}} by Constaninos Papilias, Univision, 20 Mar 2020, retrieved 29 Mar 2020</ref>\n*Odalys Ram\u00edrez, television presenter and model (''\u00a1Cu\u00e9ntamelo ya!'' and ''Al aire''; Televisa)<ref name=famous />\n*[[Camila Sodi]], 33, singer and actress<ref name=famous />\n{{End div col}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col}}\n*[[2020 in Mexico]]\n*[[2020s]]\n*[[Fourth Transformation]]\n*[[History of smallpox in Mexico]]\n*[[Cocoliztli epidemics]]\n*[[Spanish flu|1918 Spanish flu pandemic]]\n*[[2009 flu pandemic in Mexico]]\n*[[HIV/AIDS in Latin America]]\n*[[Dengue fever outbreaks]]\n*[[Epidemiology of chikungunya|2014 chikungunya outbreak in Mexico]]\n*[[2015\u20132016 Zika virus epidemic]]\n{{End div col}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Mexico]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in North America|Mexico]]\n[[Category:2020 in Mexico|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in Mexico]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in Mexico]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Mexico]]\n", "name_user": "Useight", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eApril 1 to 15:added comma", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Mexico"}
